\fs32 According to [4], collaborative filtering algorithms can be classified into 2 general classes: Memory-based and Model-based. Memory-based algorithm uses the items\'92 ratings rated by all users and users\'92 ratings rated by them- selves to compute the similarity among the users or items and then make recommendations. This mechanism is easy to implement and effective in some specific areas. However, [3] raises performance concerns as this method are not justified by a formal model and doubts the suitability of a similarity comparison among items without analysing the interactions within all the neighbours. Model-based algorithm is to build models using statistics meth- ods to find the patterns based on the training data and then use these models to make recommendations. [13] presents the techniques used in Model-based algorithms, such as Bayesian Networks, cluster models, latent factor models, Markov decision tree models, and so on. Many works, such as [9], com- bine the Memory-based and Model-based algorithms to improve prediction accuracy by utilizing the advantages of them.
